", "thumbnailwidth": "75"}, "subtype": "thumbnail", "type": "image", "width": 75, "height": 75}], "section_name": "U.S.", "word_count": "985", "source": "The New York Times", "subsection_name": null, "lead_paragraph": "Civil rights advocates say that the Michigan city\u2019s health crisis smacks of the kind of discrimination that causes the disproportionate exposure of blacks to polluted air, water and soil.", "pub_date": "2016-01-22T00:00:00Z", "news_desk": "National", "headline": {"print_headline": "A Question of Environmental Racism in Flint ", "main": "A Question of Environmental Racism in Flint "}, "print_page": "1", "snippet": "Civil rights advocates say that the Michigan city\u2019s health crisis smacks of the kind of discrimination that causes the disproportionate exposure of blacks to polluted air, water and soil.", "_id": "56a1939138f0d83189a62d3f", "slideshow_credits": null, "abstract": "Civil rights advocates say Michigan's slow and testy response to lead-polluted water in Flint, which is mainly poor and black, is due to environmental racism; city has little political power, as blacks comprise 14 percent of Michigan's population, and state government is Republican-controlled."}